04447nam a2200637Ia 9781501738999DE-B159720240426104009.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240426t20191998nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017389997 a10.7591/97815017389992doi  a(DE-B1597)534473  a(OCoLC)1178769024  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aLIT0041902bisacsh04a883/.01qOCoLC221/eng/202302161 aThalmann, William G., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Swineherd and the Bow :bRepresentations of Class in the "Odyssey" /cWilliam G. Thalmann. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2019] 4c©1998  a1 online resource (352 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMyth and Poetics00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tAcknowledgments -- tNote on Citations and Names -- tIntroduction -- tPart I. Some "Minor" Characters in the Odyssey -- t1. Relations of Dependency: Some Themes and Issues -- t2. The View from Above: The Representation of Slaves in the Odyssey -- tPart II. Oikos and Community: The Contest of the Bow -- tIntroduction to Part II: Competitive Performances -- t3. Household, Honor, and the Violence of Competition -- t4. The Contest at the Hearth: Family Values with a Vengeance -- tPart III. Paradigms and Audiences -- tIntroduction to Part III: Appropriating Paradigms -- t5. The Dark Age and Hierarchy -- t6. The Odyssey as Social Process -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Odyssey, William G. Thalmann asserts, does not describe an actual historical society at any period, but gives a selective, idiosyncratic, and contradictory picture to serve ideological ends, representing rather than reproducing social reality. The Swineherd and the Bow is an ambitious attempt to apply literary and social science theory in order to reveal Homeric epic as a form of class discourse within the context of early Greek social and political development.Drawing upon recent scholarship in archaeology and cultural anthropology, Thalmann considers the evolution of Greek culture up to the formation of the polis in the late eighth century B.C. He demonstrates that Greek society was already stratified well before that date and that the distinction between an elite and other classes was well developed. Thalmann concentrates on the representation of slaves and on the dynamics of competition and family structure in the contest of the bow to interpret the Odyssey—and, implicitly, epic poetry generally—as an intervention in the conflicts that surrounded the birth of the polis. In the interests of the aristocracy, the poem appropriates a traditional cultural paradigm, enshrined in the story of the Hero's return. The distortions of dark–age reality, he maintains, should form the basis of an historicizing reading of the poem.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 4aFolklore. 4aLiterary Studies. 4aPoetry & Criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh1 aNagy, Gregory, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Archive Pre-2000z978311053617140uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150173899940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501738999423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501738999/original  a978-3-11-053617-1  Cornell University Press Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_CL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_CL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles